{"batchcomplete":"","query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Robert_Morris_University","to":"Robert Morris University"}],"pages":{"1089523":{"pageid":1089523,"ns":0,"title":"Robert Morris University","revisions":[{"contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{about|the university in Pennsylvania|the university in Illinois|Robert Morris University Illinois}}\n{{Infobox university\n|image_name = Robert Morris University seal.png\n|image_size = 150px\n|name = Robert Morris University\n|established = 1921\n|type = [[Private school|Private]], nonsectarian\n|president = Christopher B. Howard\n|location = [[Moon Township, Pennsylvania|Moon Township]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n|country = U.S.\n|coor = {{Coord|40.520579|N|80.210688|W|type:edu|display=inline, title}}\n|undergrad = 4,144\n|postgrad = 1,037\n|faculty = 196 full-time faculty\n|campus = [[Suburb]]an, {{convert|230|acre|km2}}\n|nickname = [[Robert Morris Colonials|Colonials]]\n|athletics = NCAA Division 1 - NEC\n|mascot = RoMo\n|colors = Blue, White, and Red<br/>{{color box|#14234B}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFFFFF}}&nbsp;{{color box|#E51937}}\n|website = {{url|www.rmu.edu}}\n|endowment = $31.76 million (2015)<ref>As of June 30, 2015. {{cite web |url=http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2015_NCSE_Endowment_Market_Values.pdf|title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2015 Endowment Market Value and Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2014 to FY 2015 |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and Commonfund Institute |year=2016}}</ref>\n|logo = [[File:Robert Morris University logo.png|250px]]\n}}\n\n'''Robert Morris University''' ('''RMU''') is a private, coeducational [[university]] located in [[Moon Township, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Moon]], a suburb of [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]. The school was founded in 1921. It enrolls more than 4,000 undergraduates and more than 1,000 graduate students and offers more than 60 bachelor's degree programs<ref>{{cite web|title=RMU undergraduate academic offerings|url=http://www.rmu.edu/Undergraduate/AcademicOfferings|website=RMU website|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> and more than 20 master's and doctoral programs.<ref>{{cite web|title=RMU graduate academic offerings|url=http://www.rmu.edu/Graduate/programs|website=RMU website}}</ref> Most students are from the Pittsburgh area, while 17 percent of freshmen in 2014 are from outside Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Class of 2018|url=http://www.rmu.edu/news_highlights.aspx?id=642|website=RMU News website|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nRobert Morris University is named after [[Robert Morris (financier)|Robert Morris]], a signer of the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]] and financier of the [[American Revolution]]. It is not affiliated with [[Robert Morris University (Illinois)|Robert Morris University-Illinois]].\n\n==History==\nRobert Morris University originated in 1921 as the '''Pittsburgh School of Accountancy''', founded by Andrew Blass. It was based in various downtown buildings during its early decades, including the William Penn Hotel.\n\nIn 1962 the school purchased Pine Hill Manor and Farm in [[Moon Township, Pennsylvania]], formerly the home of Oliver Kaufmann, vice president of [[Kaufmann's]] department store in Pittsburgh, his wife, Freda, and their children.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hands of time doom mansion|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2002&dat=19910524&id=67ciAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KbUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2771,4801786|website=Beaver County Times 5/24/91 p. A8 on Google|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> The Commonwealth of Pennsylvania then granted the school permission to award associate degrees, and the school became '''Robert Morris Junior College'''. The first new buildings, Franklin Center and three residence halls, were erected in 1963. The school became '''Robert Morris College''' in 1969, and for decades operated two separate campuses. In 2002, it attained university status and was thus renamed '''Robert Morris University'''.<ref>http://www.rmu.edu/about-rmu/rmu-history-heritage</ref> In 2010, the university sold its Downtown Center at 600 Fifth Avenue to [[Duquesne University]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert Morris sells building to Duquesne University|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/stories/2010/09/27/daily43.html?page=all|website=Pittsburgh Business Times October 1, 2010|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn Dec. 4, 2014, Gregory G. Dell'Omo announced that he had accepted an offer from [[Rider University]] to become its next president in August 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Guza|first1=Megan|title=RMU president resigns to become president of NJ university|url=http://triblive.com/news/adminpage/7305415-74/university-president-rmu#axzz3LhslHCFS|accessdate=12 December 2014|agency=Pittsburgh Tribune-Review}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Schackner|first1=Bill|title=RMU president gets new job at Rider University|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/education/2014/12/04/Robert-Morris-University-president-Dell-Omo-leaving-for-Rider-University/stories/201412040288|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> The university at that time announced plans for the formation of a presidential search committee.  On Sept. 10, 2015, Robert Morris named  [[Christopher B. Howard|Christopher Howard]], currently president of Hampden-Sydney College, as its next president.  Howard, the first African-American president in school history, assumed office in February 2016.\n\n==Campus==\nThe core campus consists of a 230-acre (0.93&nbsp;km\u00b2) tract in [[Moon Township]], [[Pennsylvania]], a suburb of [[Pittsburgh]] near [[Pittsburgh International Airport]]. Of the 21 instructional and administrative buildings, the newest are the Scaife Center's School of Nursing building, opened in 2015, and the Wheatley Center, opened in 2012.<ref>[http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/local/neighborhoods-west/dual-success-robert-morris-opens-building-reaches-fundraising-goal-655067/]</ref> Of 14 residence halls, three are newer apartment-style complexes; the university also has converted a former hotel nearby into Yorktown Hall, now entirely student housing. More than 2,000 students live in campus housing, including 86 percent of freshmen.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Class of 2018|url=http://www.rmu.edu/news_highlights.aspx?id=642|website=RMU website news|accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe main building on campus is the Edward A. Nicholson Student Center, or Nicholson Center for short, and consists of four main levels. The Ground Level, which contains a Barnes and Noble Bookstore that doubles as a school spirit store. The Mezzanine Level, which houses the PNC Cafe as well as the Office for Student Life, the mail room, and Center for Student Success. The Plaza Level, which contains the Admissions Office, Heritage Room, and RoMo's Cafe. The Library Level, which consists of the School of Education and Social Sciences, and lounge areas. The Nicholson Center is attached to the Patrick Henry Center, which has recently undergone exterior renovations. <ref>http://studentlife.rmu.edu/</ref>\n\nThe library is on the second and third floors of the Patrick Henry Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sentry.rmu.edu/web/cms/schools/library/about/Pages/locations.aspx|title=Locations|accessdate=2013-08-28}}</ref> RMU participates in inter-library lending consortia PALINET and PALCI that allow RMU students to borrow books on site from most of the college and university libraries in the Pittsburgh area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sentry.rmu.edu/web/cms/academics/library/about/Pages/faq.aspx|title=Frequently Asked Questions|accessdate=2010-01-03}}</ref>\n\nThe School of Business Complex was opened in the Fall of 2011, and contains The PNC Trading Center, The United States Steel Corporation Video Conferencing and Technology Center, and the ATI Center, as well as a number of classroom's and the President's Office. The building also houses 12 Bloomberg Terminals, and an 18-seat Cisco telepresence room which enables videoconferencing experience. <ref>http://www.rmu.edu/News.aspx?id=127</ref> \n\nThe [[84 Lumber Arena]] is the home of the men's and women's [[ice hockey]] teams at the RMU Island Sports Center, a {{convert|32|acre|m2}} sports and recreation facility located on [[Neville Township, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Neville Island]] in the [[Ohio River]] {{convert|9|mi}} from [[Downtown Pittsburgh]]. The center is open to the public year-round and contains two indoor and two outdoor ice rinks, an indoor hockey arena (home to the Steel City Icebergs), and a sports and golf dome, which accommodates an indoor golf driving range and field sports including soccer, lacrosse, softball, and youth baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rmuislandsports.org/web/cms/isc/facility-rental/Pages/golf-and-sports-dome.aspx|title=Golf and Sports Dome|accessdate=2010-01-03}}</ref> The Center also has an outdoor 18-hole miniature golf course.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rmuislandsports.org/web/cms/isc/mini-golf/Pages/default.aspx|title=Miniature Golf |accessdate=2010-01-03}}</ref>\n\nThe university also has classes at its Downtown campus at 339 Sixth Avenue in Pittsburgh, also the home of the Bayer Center for Nonprofit Management at Robert Morris University.\n\n==Academics==\nRMU offers 49 undergraduate and 35 graduate degree programs, as well as three doctoral programs. The university consists of five academic schools:\n# the School of Business offers undergraduate and graduate degree programs, which are AACSB accredited<ref>[http://sbus.rmu.edu/ School of Business]</ref><ref name=\"RMUSOBAACSB\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rmu.edu/web/cms/academics/sbu/Pages/default.aspx|title=RMU AACSB School of Business |publisher=Robert Morris University |accessdate=2009-04-08}}</ref>\n# the School of Education and Social Sciences (TEAC accredited) offers undergraduate, graduate, and doctoral degree programs.<ref>[http://sess.rmu.edu/ School of Education and Social Sciences]</ref>\n# the School of Nursing and Health Sciences offers undergraduate, graduate, and doctoral degree programs.<ref>[http://snhs.rmu.edu/ School of Nursing and Health Sciences]</ref>\n# the School of Communications and Information Systems offers undergraduate (ABET accredited), graduate, and doctoral degree programs<ref>[http://scis.rmu.edu/ School of Communications and Information Systems]</ref>\n# the School of Engineering, Mathematics, and Science offers undergraduate degree programs, including ABET-accredited engineering programs, and one graduate program.<ref>[http://sems.rmu.edu/ School of Engineering, Mathematics, and Science]</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n{{See also|Robert Morris Colonials}}\n{{See also|Robert Morris Colonials men's basketball}}\nRobert Morris' sports teams, nicknamed \"the Colonials\", use the school colors of blue and white. The Colonials compete in [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] Division I ([[Football Championship Subdivision|FCS]], formerly Division I-AA, in football). Most of the school's sports participate in [[Northeast Conference]]. The men's ice hockey team competes in [[Atlantic Hockey]], women's ice hockey team is a member of the [[College Hockey America]], and women's rowing, which competes in the [[Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference]].\n\nRobert Morris field men's teams in: basketball, football, golf, ice hockey, lacrosse, and soccer. Women's teams are:  basketball, cheerleading, cross country, ice hockey, lacrosse, rowing, soccer, softball, track & field, and volleyball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rmucolonials.com/HomePage.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=13900&SPLASH_SET=YES|title=Official Site of Robert Morris Athletics |accessdate=2010-01-03}}</ref>\n\nAs of the fall 2016 semester all athletic teams official uniform provider will be Under Armour.\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Presidents of Robert Morris University==\nThe following is a li